  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering in several key ways:\n\n1. International Agreements and Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Establish global standards for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate on investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Share financial intelligence and evidence across borders\n- Extradition of individuals involved in financial crimes\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Encourage consistent anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Standardize reporting requirements\n- Create similar legal frameworks across jurisdictions\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- International monitoring of national AML efforts\n- Peer review processes\n- Sanctions for non-compliance\n\n5. Information Sharing\n- International financial intelligence units\n- Cross-border communication networks\n- Real-time data exchange about suspicious transactions\n\n6. Jurisdictional Cooperation\n- Address challenges of transnational financial crimes\n- Coordinate investigations across different legal systems\n- Prevent \"safe havens\" for money laundering\n\n7. Legal Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- International criminal court provisions\n- Coordinated prosecution strategies\n\nThese intersections create a complex global approach to combating financial crime.",
